article.headline: Washington State 57, Arizona State 55
article.story: PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) -- Washington State hasn't won many basketball games during Thomas Kelati's four years as a Cougar, but Kelati can always say he was perfect on Senior Day. Kelati, one of three seniors playing his final home game, set up fellow senior Chris Schlatter for a game-winning 3-pointer with approximately 9 seconds left in the Cougars' 57-55 triumph over Arizona State on Saturday. "We knew this one was very crucial if we are going to go to the Pac-10 Tournament," said Kelati, who finished 4-0 in Washington State's Senior Day games. Kelati led the Cougars (11-14, 6-10 Pac-10) with 15 points. Jeff Varem added 13, Schlatter had nine, and Varem grabbed the rebound at game's end after Arizona State's Tyrone Jackson missed a running jump shot from short range. Schlatter and Varem are transfers who did not play four years at Washington State. Ike Diogu paced Arizona State (18-10, 7-9 Pac-10) with 19 points. Diogu came into the game leading the Pac-10 with 22.5 points and 9.9 rebounds per game, but he scored just six points in the first half and finished the game with five rebounds. "I don't think I've ever seen anyone have a better game defensively against a great player than Chris Schlatter had in the first half," Washington State coach Dick Bennett said. "I think he (Schlatter) wore down a little bit in the second half, and Ike revved it up." The Cougars led 31-19 at halftime. "That is as well as we can play," Bennett said. But Diogu capped a 9-0 Arizona State run with an offensive rebound to give the Sun Devils their first lead at 44-43 with 6:09 to go. Kelati missed a 13-foot jumper with 20 seconds left, but Robbie Cowgill tipped the rebound to Kelati. The Cougars had regained possession with 36 seconds left after Varem forced Diogu into a turnover and shot-clock violation. "I tried to make a move; I thought they might call a foul," Diogu said. "They weren't calling anything." The 55-point total was a season low for Arizona State. The Sun Devils went to a full-court press in the second half and forced 11 of Washington State's 17 turnovers with increased defensive pressure all over the court. "In the first half, we were pretty much letting them dictate the tempo," Diogu said. "In the second half, we played more our style." "I think a great deal of credit goes to Arizona State for coming back," Bennett said, "because we played perhaps our best half of basketball at both ends of the floor in the first half." The Cougars had lost four straight games, and they were winless in their last seven games decided by three points or less. "A loss would have been devastating," Kelati said.
